│ stop({"edit_points": [[1534, 1535,                                          │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp"]], "thoughts":    │
│ "1. Understanding the Issue: The problem occurs when InstCombine transforms │
│ a select instruction that represents a logical AND of two floating-point    │
│ comparisons into a fabs-based comparison. The original code has `%cmp1 =    │
│ fcmp ninf olt float %x, small_positive` and `%cmp2 = fcmp ogt float %x,     │
│ small_negative`, with the select implementing `cmp2 ? cmp1 : false`. This   │
│ is equivalent to checking if x is in the range (small_negative,             │
│ small_positive). The transformation converts this to `fabs(x) <             │
│ small_positive`, but incorrectly handles FastMathFlags (FMF).\n\nThe issue  │
│ manifests with input x = -infinity. In the source: cmp1 is poison (because  │
│ -inf < small_positive with ninf flag produces poison), cmp2 is false (-inf  │
│ > small_negative is false), so the select returns false. In the target:     │
│ fabs(-inf) with ninf flag produces poison, so the comparison returns        │
│ poison. This makes the target more poisonous than the source.\n\n2.         │
│ Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows that the transformation happens in     │
│ foldBooleanAndOr -> foldLogicOfFCmps. The key observation is that LHS       │
│ (%cmp1) has ninf FMF while RHS (%cmp2) doesn't have any FMF. The            │
│ transformation at lines 1534-1535 unions the FMF (`LHS->getFastMathFlags()  │
│ | RHS->getFastMathFlags()`), but this is incorrect for logical              │
│ selects.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: In foldLogicOfFCmps, when handling the  │
│ range check idiom (lines 1505-1541), the code unions the FastMathFlags from │
│ both comparisons when creating the fabs instruction. However, for logical   │
│ operations (IsLogical=true), we cannot safely union FMF because it may      │
│ introduce additional poison. The comment at line 1449 in the same function  │
│ notes \"TODO: We can union the fast math flags unless this is a logical     │
│ select\", but this TODO wasn't addressed in the range check                 │
│ transformation.\n\nThe specific issue is that the lhs comparison has ninf   │
│ FMF, which means it's poison for infinity inputs. The rhs comparison has no │
│ FMF, so it's well-defined for all inputs. When we create fabs with unioned  │
│ FMF (including ninf), the fabs becomes poison for infinity inputs, making   │
│ the entire expression more poisonous than the original.\n\n4. Proposed Edit │
│ Point(s): The fix is to intersect FMF instead of unioning them when         │
│ IsLogicalSelect is true, similar to how it's handled in the earlier part of │
│ foldLogicOfFCmps (lines 1451-1452). For non-logical cases, unioning is      │
│ safe, but for logical selects, we must be conservative and intersect.\n\n5. │
│ Conclusion: By changing the FMF handling in the range check transformation  │
│ to intersect flags when dealing with logical selects, we ensure that the    │
│ transformed code doesn't introduce additional poison. This maintains the    │
│ poison semantics equivalence between source and target while still allowing │
│ the beneficial optimization for non-logical cases."})                       │
